Below is a complete, student-friendly project brief you can give directly to your students. It’s designed for Java, uses ArrayList for storage, and forces them to apply all OOP pillars and SOLID principles.

🧑‍💼 Employee Management System (OOP + SOLID Project)
📌 Project Overview
Build a console-based Employee Management System that allows an organization to manage employees, their roles, salaries, and performance using Object-Oriented Programming principles and SOLID design principles.

👉 Data storage must use ArrayList (no database, no files).

🎯 Learning Objectives
By completing this project, the student should demonstrate:

Encapsulation
Inheritance
Polymorphism
Abstraction
SOLID principles (S, O, L, I, D)
Proper class design
Clean and maintainable code
Use of ArrayList for in-memory storage
⚙️ Functional Requirements
1️⃣ Employee Management
The system should allow the user to:

Add a new employee
View all employees
Search for an employee by ID
Update employee details
Remove an employee
Calculate salary
2️⃣ Employee Types (Inheritance + Polymorphism)
There should be different types of employees:

Full-Time Employee
Part-Time Employee
Contract Employee
Each employee type should calculate salary differently.

3️⃣ Menu System
A console menu like:

1. Add Employee ✅
2. View All Employees ✅
3. Search Employee (By name) ✅ By Id
4. Update Employee
5. Delete Employee
6. Calculate Salary
7. Exit
All fields must be private
Access data using getters and setters
Validate input (e.g. salary must not be negative)
Polymorphism

ArrayList<Employee>

Call calculateSalary() without knowing the actual employee type
SOLID Principles (Mandatory)

Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

Each class must have one responsibility.

Examples:

Employee → employee data
SalaryCalculator → salary logic
EmployeeService → business logic
EmployeeMenu → user interaction
Open/Closed Principle (OCP)

You should be able to add a new employee type without modifying existing code.
Example: Add InternEmployee later with no changes to core logic.
Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Create small, focused interfaces.

Example:
interface Payable {
double calculateSalary();
}

Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)

High-level classes should depend on interfaces
Example:

interface EmployeeRepository {
void add(Employee employee);
ArrayList<Employee> getAll();
}

